===Glyph origin===
{{Han etyl}}

{{Han compound|爪|卩|ls=ic|t1=claw; hand|t2=kneeling person}}. It depicts a hand pressing down on a kneeling person. {{zh-l|*色}} was an ancient form of {{zh-l|*印}}; they both originally meant "to press down", meaning now written with {{zh-l|*抑}}. The character was later borrowed phonetically to mean "color".

''{{w|Shuowen}}'' interprets this character as an {{Han compound|人|卪|ls=ic|t1=person; human|nocap=y}}, which refers to the expression, vitality or complexion of a person's face.

Sometimes, especially in folk etymology, the character is misinterpreted as a proto-form of {{och-l|*絕}}. The bottom part is unrelated to {{och-l|*巴}}.

===Etymology===
Possibly from {{inh-lite|zh|sit-pro|*srək||ashamed; shy}}, whence {{cog-lite|my|sc=Mymr|ရှက်||tr=hrak|ashamed; shy}}, {{cog-lite|sit-jap|tɤ-zraʁ||shame}} ({{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}; {{zh-ref|Jacques, 2015b}}).

Alternatively, {{zh-ref|Schuessler (2007)}} connects this word to {{cog-lite|lus|sâr||prismatic colours seen in the sky in fine weather; to be healthy-looking, ruddy}}, which would point to a form ''*sər-k'' from which the Old Chinese was derived.

{{och-l|彩|colour|tr=*s.r̥ˤəʔ}} may be a dialectal variant ({{zh-ref|Baxter, 1992}}; {{zh-ref|Baxter and Sagart, 2014}}).

